    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, can you help me understand the difference between a \"confidentiality period\" and a \"survival clause\" in a standard contract? I'm trying to make sure I don't miss anything important.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Of course! A confidentiality period in a contract is a time frame during which the parties involved must keep certain information secret. It's like a time limit for keeping a secret, but in this case, it's about not sharing sensitive details. On the other hand, a survival clause is a bit like a protective spell that ensures certain terms of the contract, like confidentiality, continue to exist even after the contract ends. It's like having a little piece of the contract's soul that survives beyond its physical lifespan. So, while the confidentiality period is about keeping secrets for a set time, the survival clause is about keeping those secrets alive even after the contract's time has passed.",
      "source": "target",
